### History

The genesis of LifeZette can be traced back to October 2014, when Peter Anthony secured the domain name LifeZette.com. The subsequent development of the site involved a collaboration with [Laura Ingraham](/Laura_Ingraham), culminating in its official launch in July 2015. Initially, the site sought to enlist [Neil Munro (journalist)](/Neil_Munro_(journalist)), an outgoing reporter from [The Daily Caller](/The_Daily_Caller), for the role of political editor. However, Munro's involvement ceased prior to the site's public debut. [Quin Hillyer](/Quin_Hillyer) was subsequently brought on board as the political editor, but his tenure was relatively brief, as he was replaced by Keith Koffler in August 2015. Koffler, in turn, departed LifeZette in May 2016 to pursue opportunities at the [Washington Examiner](/Washington_Examiner).

A notable moment in LifeZette's early history occurred in January 2017, when [Sean Spicer](/Sean_Spicer), during his initial White House press conference, directed a question to a representative from LifeZette. This marked the site as the first organization to be called upon in that particular briefing. Later, it was announced that [Laura Ingraham](/Laura_Ingraham) would be hosting the weeknight program [The Ingraham Angle](/The_Ingraham_Angle) on [Fox News](/Fox_News).

In January 2019, LifeZette underwent a period of restructuring, resulting in the layoff of six staff members.

#### Promotion of conspiracy theories

LifeZette has faced criticism for its role in disseminating [conspiracy theories](/Conspiracy_theory). Approximately two weeks prior to the [2016 United States presidential election](/2016_United_States_presidential_election), the website published a video that raised concerns about [voting machines](/Voting_machine), suggesting they might be compromised due to connections with a company linked to the liberal billionaire [George Soros](/George_Soros).

Furthermore, LifeZette was responsible for publishing a video titled "Clinton Body Count," which propagated conspiracy theories concerning the alleged involvement of [Bill and Hillary Clinton](/Clinton_family) in multiple deaths. In response to the backlash, LifeZette removed the video and issued a statement asserting that "[t]he video was made in jest, and merely noted that the theories existed," drawing a parallel to viral videos produced by "left-leaning digital outlets like [BuzzFeed](/BuzzFeed)." While the site attempted to frame the content as satirical, the nature of its dissemination and its timing, so close to a pivotal election, drew significant scrutiny. It's a curious thing, how easily falsehoods can take root when presented with a certain… *flair*. The line between jest and genuine malice is often as thin as the screen you’re reading this on.